		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Game Programming
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1831515">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Wool</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=ef035035ca80ac30c4a1f3dbbb883709&amp;p=1831510#post1831510" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">I am curious what is going on to spur such a  decision. The unreal 4 engine has already seemed dominate in my eyes  with the number of titles using it. Even Japanese games use that engine  now!<br />
<br />
<br />
I used to make maps in Unreal Editor when I was in high school, but have  never been able to grasp anything more modern or complicated. I've  wanted to make a simple 2D game for awhile now, but never find the time  for it. <br />
<br />
So right now, there are four more competitors for this space, if I remember correctly. <br />
<br />
Unreal 4<br />
CryEngine<br />
Unity<br />
Game Maker</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>It is extremely crafty on their part. Their is no downside for them  financially, it immediately makes the Unreal 4 engine the de facto  platform for any educational material, it has none of the downsides that  Unity has with respect to homogeneity across platforms related to  historical and ongoing discrepancies between Mono and Microsoft's Common  Language Runtime. <br />
<br />
Microsoft's CEO (Satya Nadella) is thankfully  unfucking their platform strategies and making them available  everywhere regardless of underlying environment (Android, iOS, Linux, OS  X, Windows, etc.) and converging towards that goal rather than  antagonizing the very people who the platforms are entirely reliant upon  for making worthwhile, the relevance here being that all of the warts  related to Mono and the Common Language Runtime discrepancies would no  longer be relevant, and the CLR will increasingly find its way onto  resumes (because MS is no longer trying to lock people into a platform  through their tool or app selections and those same tools can be reused  in other contexts which is desirable), meaning that there will be a  greater amount of people who can take advantage of Unity without having  to take time to understand the CLR first because they will already know  it beforehand.<br />
<br />
However, making this move now, UE heads off this  change entirely, rendering it moot, and guaranteeing they still what  would have been potential inertia for another platform having done the  same. It is genius and everyone wins regardless of background and means.  The licensing cost is exceedingly reasonable as well regardless of  global location and income. And it ensures as much expertise remains  with Unreal Engine rather than another selection. Which is no small  thing, consider how even John Carmack with all of his (at the time) pull  at Id Software realized trying to steer people with thousands of hours  of time sunk into one platform towards another was the way of mutiny.  So, it is paramount that UE is used as early as possible so that that  becomes what the person is comfortable in and is exceedingly resistant  to switching away from (which is likely reasonable). <br />
<br />
The nice  thing about how this is all set up at present is that there are no traps  set in the arrangement or fine print inlaid with dragons be here. For  myself what I am most ecstatic about is that it will serve as another  data point to encourage other proprietary platforms to make their source  code available in a similar manner so that fixing bugs and making  changes is trivial rather than a months to never turn around time.<br />
<br />
It's  like, I want to pay whomever money for their product, but at the same  time, when they are not following a similar pattern to the way UE4 is  made available commercially, everyone loses in the short and long run;  in the long run, enormous amounts of man hours are lost relearning how  to do the same thing after a product is abandoned (which has never not  happened, no exceptions) or that utility simply no longer exists in the  future (see many examples by any of your favorite companies) because  reasons almost always hand waved into being; in the short run,  documentation is much worse, fixing bugs is significantly more arduous  and when accomplished most assuredly breaks between updates, and  tailoring the tools to fit how the real world actually works in our  context is made impossible! <br />
<br />
The last is the most egregious as no plugin  architecture or developer API will ever be sufficient for encompassing  what is trivially made possible through simply releasing the damn source  code rather than wasting time attempting and failing at being  exceedingly clever. The way this most concretely unwittingly maligns the  people selling the product is that not doing so greatly hinders the  capacity for an culture to develop around the product and increase that  product's value tremendously. Immediately, it is impossible to have confidence that a given proprietary API or architecture will exist in the future, as has been made evident repeatedly, perhaps most loudly through the cries of tyranny over Facebook, Twitter, or Netflix changing or removing their developer APIs to what should have been to the surprise of no one but the universe is loathed to learn from experience.<br />
<br />
So, this is a sweet situation, I  will be extremely surprised if some exceptional open online courses  (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massive_open_online_course" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massiv..._online_course</a>) do not appear  within the year which use UE4 throughout; it would make for an  exceptional and comprehensive computer science curriculum as well, even  through a PhD or Masters. It will tie in to other areas which would not  have utilized anything as mature also, such as gamification efforts. It  just became the de facto tool for many contexts and it will be extremely difficult for anyone to overtake its inertia now.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
