					Re: Game Programming
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1831524">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>MI Redeux</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=ef035035ca80ac30c4a1f3dbbb883709&amp;p=1831488#post1831488" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message"><a href="https://www.unrealengine.com/blog/ue4-is-free" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">https://www.unrealengine.com/blog/ue4-is-free</a><br />
<br />
Then unreal 4 engine has been made free, complete with docs. Were I starting someone off programming I would go through game programming; the reason being, if someone is a competent game programmer and proficient in C++, they are also going to be very competent or transfer readily to system's programming. I realized a few months ago that the C++ game programming community has the largest concentration of expertise when it comes to systems programming other than more esoteric demographics (embedded systems engineering, hardware development, reverse engineering). The end result being, the person will be very proficient at both how computers actually work, debugger/code analysis tools (extreme time savers), task automation, and other very excellent skills for contributing towards other domains. And as there is a dearth of recent graduates who actually understand how computers work and are competent this is an excellent insight.<br />
<br />
The entire engine being readily available for a tremendously reasonable pricing is excellent and it will provide an excellent reference for real-world, low-level, algorithm intensive, and complex c++ code for people to learn from.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Out of curiosity, how do you feel about game programming teaching bad software programming practices?  I feel like most people I meet in the software development world who come from game development backgrounds and fairly universal in their admission that games are generally not programmed well from a software perspective.  But I probably have a biased group of people who I can ask about such issues.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
