		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Game Programming
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1831531">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Ikeya</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=ef035035ca80ac30c4a1f3dbbb883709&amp;p=1831524#post1831524" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Out of curiosity, how do you feel about game  programming teaching bad software programming practices?  I feel like  most people I meet in the software development world who come from game  development backgrounds and fairly universal in their admission that  games are generally not programmed well from a software perspective.   But I probably have a biased group of people who I can ask about such  issues.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>I have not done any notable game programming other than in a strict  concept of game; I am excited about this development though as hopefully  newcomers going through a platform that is also an industrial one and  the domain forcing those who want to develop the skillset (game  programming)  to also gain proficiency in mathematics and applying the  relevant maths to many real, modeled problems and writing and testing  low level code that is absent handwaving as to what the written text  actually corresponds to. I expect that people coming from such a  background in the future will have acquired the disposition always  associated with previous generations which is to be a voracious consumer  and synthesize of information and always be improving regardless of  whether a specific knowledge domain is seemingly relevant. <br />
<br />
The  typical case among younger workers of being exceedingly happy with  having learned and gained proficiency at a desired ability at this exact  point in time and saying fuck it with respect to all other future and  past knowledge is demoralizing; external to how useful such a person is,  we know without further information that the field will reinforce upon  the same patterns rather than progressing in step with the latest field  research. <br />
<br />
The thirty year or longer delay between publications  and it actually having an impact on industry practice is indefensibly  insane when it addresses and directly rectifies a then current issue: if  you want to see this in action, look no further than the waves of  people falling upon the sword of OOP despite this having no relation in  the world elsewhere and being exceedingly difficult to verify behaves  according to how the implementer (programmer in this case) intended. <br />
<br />
In  general, if something has no pair to a pattern in nature or language,  there is an extremely great chance it is not going to lead to a desired  outcome or not setting traps wrought with malice. It is not necessarily  true, but precise attention needs paid to ensure the path is not leading  the host over a cliff for decades and leaving no escape hatch to rescue  ourselves from or we are not ignoring an easier method along the way,  and there is likely prizes or medals involved upon it being verified as  conforming to our intentions.<br />
<br />
People not having this attitude is  something I take extreme exception to; never in the history of ever has  learning a new skill when the opportunity arises proven useless  regardless of its irrelevance and utter waste of time it would appear on  its face to an external observer and only has acquiring that skill been  possible to do efficiently at all because I focused entirely on  learning categories of information rather than a specific implementation  of that information, the former being considerably and ongoingly  maligned in press despite being the only way to effectively cope with  changes in an engineering field. <br />
<br />
Aside: case in point, just  learn and understand abstract algebra and category theory already; it is  going to be enormously more useful and life impacting than slogging  through effortful descriptions of what a shadow. <br />
<br />
And yes, this  is a sharp task if the person is not used to reading formal technical  documents, however, this is an of itself is a skill that pays for itself  repeatedly and it also has an ancillary benefit of its own. And no  burritos need be wasted along the way; instead everyone now knows all of  tex-mex cuisine and can make their own burritos or riffs upon them,  perhaps publish a paper on arxiv along the way at some point. I know  this is possible, I have done it and I am idiot; have faith you can too  fellow human and be much more efficient.<br />
<br />
Specifically, rather  than learning directly through an approximation of a technique or  concept described, such as with the learn x in 15 minutes or y for  'hackers' (scare quotes very intended), read and understand what the  specific example is derived from that way an entire category of  information which will never be invalidated (in the context of maths  anyways) is instilled rather than a specific implementation of that  category which will inevitably be reimplemented with a slight wrinkle in  a myriad ways and also avoid hitting an avoidable wall in the future as expertise in the domain expands.<br />
<br />
It's  an utter waste of time to do otherwise and leads to the overwhelming  noise outside publications among other malignant side effects, such as  the presumption that someone who does not know x of y does not know y  despite having advertised w of y as a skill, concretely I am referring  to the meme that old people can't code anymore because they are not hip  to the latest hop. There are many others.<br />
<br />
Anyways, bringing it  back to the initial point, in addition to specifically teaching many  domains intrinsic to programming, a hypothetical pedagogy can also use  the platform to perform simulations when instilling understanding of not  necessarily related maths rather than utilizing IPython, Mathematica,  Matlab etc. as I had promoted in the past as being the one true way to  instill the actual understanding that is almost always unaccomplished  with the way maths are taught now. <br />
<br />
As food for thought: given  that maths are without equal in their usefulness in exactly all aspects  of life without exception* and given that there exists no beauty  comparable to maths anywhere external to maths, that nearly everyone is  horrified of maths or has an unparalleled disdain for all numbers is  symptomatic of the processes utilized themselves being incompetent  rather than the people who are compelled to make an effort as is and has  been claimed. <br />
<br />
Intentionally or otherwise leading persons to  refute maths entirely is akin to forcing people to refute all languages  and being sated that everyone save rounding error is disallowed to  experience actual beauty. <br />
<br />
Poetically that is horrifying,  pragmatically most everyone being made cripple and tasked with existence  is an absurd event being allowed and accepted as inevitable.<br />
<br />
*  There does not exist any system which cannot be analyzed and  characteristics of that system being derived completely or concrete  statements being made which describe what is knowable about the system,  either of which is useful for making decisions. As an example knowing  something is unknowable enables realizing people who claim an unknowable  event is known and plausibly stating what is known exactly are either  being purposefully malicious i.e. the dreaded confidence man or the  professor is compromised in some manner that it is useful to be wary of  in the future when interacting with them i.e. I should probably fact  check someone who does not have a medical degree or even practical  expertise when they say pot pies cure cancer or that someone smoked a  million marijuanas and murdered their family. <br />
<br />
Knowing things  about things without knowing anything about the thing because we can  rule out or have our attention drawn to characteristics claimed of the  thing or greatly narrow down what is plausible. Without having developed  such an ability and through practice gained confidence that our  application there of is sound, there would be no way to have complete  confidence in an assessment that survives being entirely marginalized at  a specific point in time. At best we could be extremely cocksure that  for some reason our chemical reactions are special and intrinsically  enlightening or simply magical. In the case of filtering information  out, we would otherwise have to resort to improbable chance of a  selection being appropriate or expending tremendous energy trying all  possibilities.<br />
<br />
Imagine if you never knew of bacon or wet ribs or  dry ribs and because of such ignorance only ever consumed Soylent Green  as an energy source. There is of course nothing wrong with having a  Soylent Green preference, it is incredibly reasonable to have such a  preference, but to effectively deny everyone pork products is anathema  to good governance. In the same way, it is imperative and necessary for  realizing good outcomes for everyone to know when to apply maths and  what is of use in a situation as part of their daily consciousness as an  ongoing tool in their social makeup. <br />
<br />
In summary, Unreal Engine 4  will transform the United States of America from working from hysteria  and what the emotions want towards a measured data driven system and  reduce the likelihood of making an initially bad choice and ensure that  bad choices are subjected to replacement when it becomes obvious rather  than continuing to reinforce the same poor choice to the order of  consuming resources which would have lead to a failed state for most  currently existing countries.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
	</div>
