		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Game Programming
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1832770">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							My efforts to spread the truth with respect to improvements in efficacy (long term learning retention and capacity to quickly grok new domains) has yet to have any effect upon the demographic I wish to reach, namely one of my best friends who is the most anti-math person in the universe, additionally he has no love for linguistics. <br />
<br />
Pointing out how he uses both everyday and the mappings between the contexts and the underlying forms has been completely uncompelling. Currently he is struggling with grokking concepts introduced by a multi-paradigm language (Scala) which his expertise in Java is not inclusive of and as a result he is not really keeping up with his peers on the team which do. So, currently I have ran out of strategies for compelling him to this direction in order to improve his game; additionally he does not give a single fuck about learning the underlying CS designs in order to understand the new contexts through reading the source code for the language.<br />
<br />
This attitude is regrettably the majority amongst programmers; I would think at minimum they would appreciate how it would help them avoid running into a wall and be able to understand research much faster. However even basic concepts escape them in practice which leads to a lot of the noise in forums. I have been shocked by how badly people are understanding machine learning concepts that are not researchers in the field. <br />
<br />
Even with an introduction book that has decent coverage their understanding is worse than that. It's very infuriating, well more accurately described as disappointing, not because I think everyone should be 100% into machine learning but because many of the concepts covered, the underlying concepts they should know if they have a CS degree. They only need basic statistics, linear algebra, and calculus, as well as at least a decent grasp of some physics and biological systems but nothing past a 101 course in those; all of which they should already have been exposed to and digested.<br />
<br />
I think I have uncovered why this attitude emerges though and I cannot really put them at fault for it; however I do think I have a way to reduce the probability that it occurs. It's not something that is directly resolvable due to the relevant literature not existing to support it, but with the proper environment available that has low friction it should happen. I am optimistic for 2 generations for now that enter industry at least assuming the reference material problem gets resolved. <br />
<br />
There is one very good reference for Linear Algebra and one very good reference for Discrete Mathematics. Regrettably they do not share a common language utilized and the relevant toolchain has no isometric mapping. <br />
So, that is a lot of friction incurred right away. The LA toolchain could be implemented in the DM one but I do not particularly like that solution but because of some attributes of the LA toolchain if we utilized one similar to the DM toolchain in a comprehensive course work plan that would be better I think. <br />
<br />
Conclusion: still a tremendous amount of work to do to make things better and less shitty for most people so that they get maths early on with its applications and interrelations with topics. Ideally there was a community effort for this but fragmentation is tremendously high and the driving factors will not necessarily result in the desirable conclusion. It will require a change in pedagogy variables that are maximized and a change in how courses are taught. It will need to be open source or at least very inexpensive/pro-rated in its offerings (although not necessarily gratis en total).<br />
<br />
However, the good news is, at least for people not already biased to dismiss the utility to their own applications, I think we can transfer the magic to the masses that currently do not benefit from it in their own lives and are not encapsulated in the desirable demographic that can use it effectively.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
