		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Game Programming
				</h2>
				

						
						
							
						
				<div class="content ">
					<div id="post_message_1841084">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Ikeya</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=ef035035ca80ac30c4a1f3dbbb883709&amp;p=1841023#post1841023" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Better late then never I guess.  Buuuut...<br />
<br />
<ul><li style="">Frequent copy pasting of code.  Loads of duplication.</li><li style="">Code difficult to test, particularly from an automation point of view</li><li style="">Poor dependency management</li><li style="">Overloaded function &amp; method purposes</li><li style="">Compromised clarity in favor of performance </li></ul><br />
<br />
Those would probably be my top five.  I've heard of complaints about  other aspects, but it never felt like they might be something explicitly  encouraged by the toolsets used in game programming (i.e. Bad variable  and method naming).</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>I wonder to what extent those are contributable to using very old code  and having to optimize for the very short term causes that. Reasons I  mention that, is that those are characteristics of large, old code  often. Performance and clarity are not necessarily directly related and  something I would contribute to the environment not having good  utilities or capacity for metaprogramming. Common Lisp code that  contains inline assembly, is still very readable in practice because it  is always represented in an understandable way through its compiler  macro. <br />
<br />
Even though CL's metaprogramming facilities are less  elegant and are discrete to some purpose rather than generalizing over  all facilities, I find it useful having explicit differences in the  metaprogamming usage within codes helpful for understanding what is  intended quickly compared to a homogeneous approach like Julia, some  schemes, and other languages.  A similar effect is with having algebraic  data types explicitly stated in other languages as it provides useful  documentation in and of itself and with ADTs, the ontology is more  easily determined by myself due to restrictions on how elements can vary  without being invalid.  <br />
<br />
Without those restrictions or discrete  differences what possibly can occur is unbounded and entirely reliant on  every member contributing code following manually enforced internal  practices or forcing the reader to consider a much larger set of rules  that are in play with how the code is evaluated.<br />
<br />
And for me, that  is what makes reading other people's C++ code in context of the rest of  the program arduous. I would immensely prefer if in future updates  specifications were made for code transformations to a more recent  representation of the functionality was created and C++'s enormous  mixture of how code is evaluated was belligerently excised. That is what  Ericsson did with Erlang that has proven extremely useful in  maintaining prior code is removing capability no longer needed given the  new alternative instead of keeping both capabilities within the  language spec such that the language grows significantly over time. With  Go through gofmt that is a significantly better addressed situation as  well. <br />
<br />
What I notice with C++ coders, is an ambitious pursuit of  making their code excessively complicated instead of using simple, well  known methods as well as continuing to embrace no longer relevant  features and mixing usage of alternatives and prior ways freely. It can  spiral to the extent that reading the decompiled code or source transformation to another language for the program is  more clear than reading the source code due to having the programmer  created obfuscation removed, which is dubious.<br />
<br />
I am extremely concerned that with Rust a similar outcome is going to occur despite it being a fantastic alternative for new systems programs unless a tool as competent as gofmt exists in the near future.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
				<!-- edit note -->
				<blockquote class="postcontent lastedited">
<!--					<img src="images/buttons/edit_40b.png" class="inlineimg" alt="" /> -->
					
						Last edited by MI Redeux; September 19th, 2015 at <span class="time">01:35 AM</span>.
					
					
				</blockquote>
				<!-- / edit note -->
				
                                       
                                 
				
                                        
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
	</div>
